Analyzing Accessible Names in the Search Form

02
On this page
  1. Accessible Names for Forms
    1. Checking the Form with VoiceOver on Mac
  2. Fix the SVG Icon VoiceOver Issue
  3. Applying Accessible Names to Buttons

The CampSpots homepage features a search form for the user to find a place to reserve.

Let’s investigate how accessible names are applied in the form and search button.

The search form has two inputs and a search button that includes an SVG icon of a magnifying glass.

Here’s what the rendered markup looks like in DevTools:

<!-- Home page form HTML -->
<form class="main-search form-wrap layout">
   <div class="form-field">
      <label for="place-search" class="label">Where to?</label>
      <div class="custom-input"><span class="icon-lookingglass"></span>
			<input id="place-search" type="text" placeholder="Try Oregon, Colorado...">
	 </div>
   </div>
   <div class="form-field">
      <label for="date-search" class="label">Dates</label>
      <div class="custom-input"><span class="icon-calendar"></span>
			<input id="date-search" type="text" placeholder="Enter dates">
	 </div>
   </div>
   <div class="form-field form-submit">
      <button aria-label="Search" class="btn-submit btn-lookingglass" data-testid="btn-submit">
         <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
						...
         </svg>
      </button>
   </div>
</form>

Accessible Names for Forms

The first input has an id of place-search input and a placeholder that suggests trying Oregon or Colorado.

There is also a <label> element for the input, with a value of “Where to?”.

What will the accessible name for the place search be?

When an input has a matching label, the accessible name exposed by the input will be that label’s value.

The DevTools Accessibility Inspector for the input provides a visual aide. Notice that the placeholder text has a strikethrough line, which signifies it isn’t being used as an accessible name even. The placeholder will still be read aloud as a description, which can be configured in a screen reader setting.

Instead the Name in the Accessibility Inspector indicates that it’s being labeled by label.label, which is another way of saying a <label> element with a class of “label”.

The label element includes a “for” attribute that associates it with the place search input by pointing to its id.

Labels are important to include in forms. Placeholders disappear as soon as the user interacts with them. This can cause cognitive load, as it’s possible a user could forget which field they were in and incorrectly fill the form.

Looking at the search button, there are a few things we know from the markup.

It uses the button element, which we know is keyboard focusable and operable.

The button has has an aria-label of “Search” and it only contains an svg element with an implicit role of image.

It seems like everything is fine, until it’s tested in a screen reader.

<!-- Home page form HTML -->
<div class="form-field form-submit">
  <button aria-label="Search" class="btn-submit btn-lookingglass" data-testid="btn-submit">
     <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <path ...></path>
     </svg>
  </button>
</div>
<!-- Home page form HTML -->
<div class="form-field form-submit">
  <button aria-label="Search" class="btn-submit btn-lookingglass" data-testid="btn-submit">
     <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <path ...></path>
     </svg>
  </button>
</div>

Checking the Form with VoiceOver on Mac

Opening the CampSpots homepage in Safari then opening VoiceOver with Fn + CMD + F5, navigating to the form seems to work as expected when using the Tab key.

There is an issue with Arrow keys, however. VoiceOver allows for Arrow key navigation, but it skips past the button so it is never announced.

This same SVG structure has worked in the past, but at some point VoiceOver developed this bug related to aria-labeled buttons with SVG icons as content. It’s possible it will be fixed in the future but for now it’s a gotcha to be aware of.

Fix the SVG Icon VoiceOver Issue

Until the VoiceOver bug gets fixed, we can adjust our SVG button a bit to make it work as expected.

A solution you could try is to explicitly add role="img" despite svg having the role implicitly applied. Following role requirements, when manually setting the image role you should also add an aria-label for alternative text.

Here’s what that solution looks like:

<svg 
	width="16" 
	height="16" 
	viewBox="0 0 16 16" 
	fill="none" 
	xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
	role="img"
	aria-label="Search"
>
<svg 
	width="16" 
	height="16" 
	viewBox="0 0 16 16" 
	fill="none" 
	xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
	role="img"
	aria-label="Search"
>

Applying Accessible Names to Buttons

There are numerous ways to apply accessible names for buttons, all of which could be good things to try for the VoiceOver bug we saw with the Arrow keys.

Here are some options:

  • Put an aria-label attribute on the button itself:
    • <button aria-label="...">
  • Put an aria-label attribute on a child image element, which will provide an accessible name to the parent button:
    • <button><span role="img" aria-label="..."></span></button>
  • Use [.visually-hidden](<https://github.com/marcysutton/testing-accessibility-demos/blob/main/workshop3-semantics-aria/styles.scss#L4>) on a child element with textContent inside:
    • <button><span class="visually-hidden">Text</span></button>

When the button contains an SVG child element:

  • Use the img role and aria-label approach
  • Use an SVG title to add an accessible name without rendering it visually: <svg><title>Text</title></svg>
  • Expose text content in the SVG that will be rendered visually:
    • <svg><text /></svg>
  • Mark the SVG with role=presentation and let a wrapping button provide the name.
